    "title": "Integrative Close",
    "objective": "Evaluate the learner's ability to distinguish between and select instruments for measuring cumulative energy versus instantaneous power in a real-world scenario.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To manage an electrical installation effectively, you must distinguish between the rate of doing work and the total work completed over time.",
      "A Wattmeter provides a snapshot of the power being used at any given second, similar to a speedometer.",
      "An Energy Meter (kWh meter) tracks the accumulation of that power over hours, days, or months, similar to an odometer."
    ],
    "questionText": "A factory owner is concerned about high monthly costs and wants to know both the total electricity used by the site over the last month and the exact rate of power being drawn by a large industrial fan while it is running. Explain which two specific instruments you would use for these two different measurements and why a single Wattmeter would be insufficient for the owner's billing concerns.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Use an Energy Meter (or kWh meter) to measure the total electricity used over the month.",
      "Use a Wattmeter to measure the instantaneous rate of power drawn by the fan.",
      "A Wattmeter is insufficient for billing because it only shows the power at a specific moment, whereas the Energy Meter is required to calculate the total consumption (work done) over a period of time."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about which instrument acts like a speedometer (rate) and which acts like an odometer (total distance/work)."
  }
}

